This specification also defines a new Response Mode `direct_post.jwt`, which allows for encryption to be used on top of the Response Mode `direct_post` defined in [Section 8.2](#response_mode_post). The mechanisms described in [Section 8.2](#response_mode_post) apply unless specified otherwise in this section.[¶](#section-8.3.1-1)

The Response Mode `direct_post.jwt` causes the Wallet to send the Authorization Response using an HTTP POST request instead of redirecting back to the Verifier as defined in [Section 8.2](#response_mode_post). The Wallet adds the `response` parameter containing the JWT as defined in [Section 8.3](#response_encryption) in the body of an HTTP POST request using the `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` content type. The names and values in the body MUST be encoded using UTF-8.[¶](#section-8.3.1-2)

If a Wallet is unable to generate an encrypted response, it MAY send an error response without encryption as per [Section 8.2](#response_mode_post).[¶](#section-8.3.1-3)

The following is a non-normative example of a response (omitted content shown with ellipses for display purposes only):[¶](#section-8.3.1-4)

```
POST /post HTTP/1.1
Host: client.example.org
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

response=eyJra...9t2LQ

```


[¶](#section-8.3.1-5)

The following is a non-normative example of the payload of the JWT used in the example above before encrypting and base64url encoding (omitted content shown with ellipses for display purposes only):[¶](#section-8.3.1-6)

```
{
  "vp_token": {"example_jwt_vc": ["eY...QMA"]}
}

```


[¶](#section-8.3.1-7)

### [8.4.](#section-8.4) [Transaction Data](#name-transaction-data)

The transaction data mechanism enables a binding between the user's identification/authentication and the user’s authorization, for example to complete a payment transaction, or to sign specific document(s) using QES (Qualified Electronic Signatures). This is achieved by signing the transaction data used for user authorization with the user-controlled key used for proof of possession of the Credential being presented as a means for user identification/authentication.[¶](#section-8.4-1)

The Wallet that received the `transaction_data` parameter in the request MUST include a representation or reference to the data in the respective Credential presentation. How this is done is transaction data type specific. Credential Formats can give recommendations of how to handle transaction data, such as those in [Appendix B](#format_specific_parameters).[¶](#section-8.4-2)

If the Wallet does not support `transaction_data` parameter, it MUST return an error upon receiving a request that includes it.[¶](#section-8.4-3)

### [8.5.](#section-8.5) [Error Response](#name-error-response)

The error response follows the rules as defined in \[[RFC6749](#RFC6749)\], with the following additional clarifications:[¶](#section-8.5-1)

`invalid_scope`:[¶](#section-8.5-2)

*   Requested scope value is invalid, unknown, or malformed.[¶](#section-8.5-3.1)

`invalid_request`:[¶](#section-8.5-4)

*   The request contains both a `dcql_query` parameter and a `scope` parameter referencing a DCQL query.[¶](#section-8.5-5.1)
*   The request uses the `vp_token` Response Type but does not include a `dcql_query` parameter nor a `scope` parameter referencing a DCQL query.[¶](#section-8.5-5.2)
*   The Wallet does not support the Client Identifier Prefix passed in the Authorization Request.[¶](#section-8.5-5.3)
*   The Client Identifier passed in the request did not belong to its Client Identifier Prefix, or requirements of a certain prefix were violated, for example an unsigned request was sent with Client Identifier Prefix `https`.[¶](#section-8.5-5.4)

`invalid_client`:[¶](#section-8.5-6)

*   `client_metadata` parameter defined in [Section 5.1](#new_parameters) is present, but the Wallet recognizes Client Identifier and knows metadata associated with it.[¶](#section-8.5-7.1)
*   Verifier's pre-registered metadata has been found based on the Client Identifier, but `client_metadata` parameter is also present.[¶](#section-8.5-7.2)

`access_denied`:[¶](#section-8.5-8)

*   The Wallet did not have the requested Credentials to satisfy the Authorization Request.[¶](#section-8.5-9.1)
*   The End-User did not give consent to share the requested Credentials with the Verifier.[¶](#section-8.5-9.2)
*   The Wallet failed to authenticate the End-User.[¶](#section-8.5-9.3)

This document also defines the following additional error codes and error descriptions:[¶](#section-8.5-10)

`vp_formats_not_supported`:[¶](#section-8.5-11)

*   The Wallet does not support any of the formats requested by the Verifier, such as those included in the `vp_formats_supported` registration parameter.[¶](#section-8.5-12.1)

`invalid_request_uri_method`:[¶](#section-8.5-13)

*   The value of the `request_uri_method` request parameter is neither `get` nor `post` (case-sensitive).[¶](#section-8.5-14.1)

`invalid_transaction_data`:[¶](#section-8.5-15)

*   any of the following is true for at least one object in the `transaction_data` structure:[¶](#section-8.5-16.1.1)
    
    *   contains an unknown or unsupported transaction data type value,[¶](#section-8.5-16.1.2.1)
    *   is an object of a known type but containing unknown fields,[¶](#section-8.5-16.1.2.2)
    *   contains fields of the wrong type for the transaction data type,[¶](#section-8.5-16.1.2.3)
    *   contains fields with invalid values for the transaction data type,[¶](#section-8.5-16.1.2.4)
    *   is missing required fields for the transaction data type,[¶](#section-8.5-16.1.2.5)
    *   the credential\_ids does not match, or[¶](#section-8.5-16.1.2.6)
    *   the referenced Credential(s) are not available in the Wallet.[¶](#section-8.5-16.1.2.7)

`wallet_unavailable`:[¶](#section-8.5-17)

*   The Wallet appears to be unavailable and therefore unable to respond to the request. It can be useful in situations where the user agent cannot invoke the Wallet and another component receives the request while the End-User wishes to continue the journey on the Verifier website. For example, this applies when using claimed HTTPS URIs handled by the Wallet provider in case the platform cannot or does not translate the URI into a platform intent to invoke the Wallet. In this case, the Wallet provider would return the Authorization Error Response to the Verifier and might redirect the user agent back to the Verifier website.[¶](#section-8.5-18.1)

### [8.6.](#section-8.6) [VP Token Validation](#name-vp-token-validation)

Verifiers MUST validate the VP Token in the following manner:[¶](#section-8.6-1)

1.  Validate the format of the VP Token as defined in [Section 8.1](#response-parameters).[¶](#section-8.6-2.1)
2.  Check the individual Presentations according to the specific Credential Format requested:[¶](#section-8.6-2.2.1)
    
    1.  Validate the integrity and authenticity of the Presentation and Credential.[¶](#section-8.6-2.2.2.1)
    2.  Validate that the returned Credential(s) meet all criteria defined in the query in the Authorization Request (e.g., Claims included in the presentation).[¶](#section-8.6-2.2.2.2)
    3.  Validate that all Presentations contain a cryptographic proof of Holder Binding (i.e., that they are Verifiable Presentations), unless specifically requested otherwise.[¶](#section-8.6-2.2.2.3)
    4.  For Verifiable Presentations, validate the Holder Binding, including the checks required to prevent replay described in [Section 14.1](#preventing-replay).[¶](#section-8.6-2.2.2.4)
    5.  Perform the checks required by the Verifier's policy based on the set of trust requirements such as trust frameworks it belongs to (e.g., revocation checks), if applicable.[¶](#section-8.6-2.2.2.5)
3.  Check that the set of Presentations returned satisfies all requirements defined in the Verifier's request as described in [Section 6.4](#dcql_query_lang_processing_rules).[¶](#section-8.6-2.3)

If any of the checks related to an individual Presentation fail, the effected Presentation MUST be discarded. If any of the checks pertaining to the VP Token or the overall response fails, the VP Token MUST be rejected.[¶](#section-8.6-3)

[9\.](#section-9) [Wallet Invocation](#name-wallet-invocation)
--------------------------------------------------------------

The Verifier can use one of the following mechanisms to invoke a Wallet:[¶](#section-9-1)

*   Custom URL scheme as an `authorization_endpoint` (for example, `openid4vp://` as defined in [Section 13.1.2](#openid4vp-scheme))
[¶](#section-9-2.1)
*   URL (including Domain-bound Universal Links/App link) as an `authorization_endpoint`[¶](#section-9-2.2)

For a cross device flow, either of the above options MAY be presented as a QR code for the End-User to scan using a Wallet or an arbitrary camera application on a user-device.[¶](#section-9-3)

The Wallet can also be invoked from the web or a native app using the Digital Credentials API as described in [Appendix A](#dc_api). As described in detail in [Appendix A](#dc_api), DC API provides privacy, security (see [Section 14.2](#session_fixation)), and user experience benefits (particularly in the cases where an End-User has multiple Wallets).[¶](#section-9-4)

[12\.](#section-12) [Verifier Attestation JWT](#name-verifier-attestation-jwt)
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Verifier Attestation JWT is a JWT especially designed to allow a Wallet to authenticate a Verifier in a secure and flexible manner. A Verifier Attestation JWT is issued to the Verifier by a party that Wallets trust for the purpose of authentication and authorization of Verifiers. The way this trust is established is out of scope of this specification. Every Verifier is bound to a public key, the Verifier MUST always present a Verifier Attestation JWT along with the proof of possession for this key. In the case of the Client Identifier Prefix `verifier_attestation`, the authorization request is signed with this key, which serves as proof of possession.[¶](#section-12-1)

A Verifier Attestation JWT MUST contain the following claims:[¶](#section-12-2)

*   `iss`: REQUIRED. This claim identifies the issuer of the Verifier Attestation JWT. The `iss` value MAY be used to retrieve the issuer's public key. How the trust is established between Wallet and Issuer and how the public key is obtained for validating the attestation's signature is out of scope of this specification.[¶](#section-12-3.1)
*   `sub`: REQUIRED. The value of this claim MUST be the `client_id` of the client making the Credential request.[¶](#section-12-3.2)
*   `iat`: OPTIONAL. A number representing the time at which the Verifier Attestation JWT was issued using the syntax defined in \[RFC7519\].[¶](#section-12-3.3)
*   `exp`: REQUIRED. A number representing the time at which the Verifier Attestation JWT expires using the syntax defined in \[RFC7519\]. The Wallet MUST reject any Verifier Attestation JWT with an expiration time that has passed, subject to allowable clock skew between systems.[¶](#section-12-3.4)
*   `nbf`: OPTIONAL. A number representing the time before which the token MUST NOT be accepted for processing.[¶](#section-12-3.5)
*   `cnf`: REQUIRED. This claim contains the confirmation method as defined in \[[RFC7800](#RFC7800)\]. It MUST contain a JSON Web Key \[[RFC7517](#RFC7517)\] as defined in Section 3.2 of \[[RFC7800](#RFC7800)\]. This claim determines the public key that the Verifier MUST prove possession of the corresponding private key for when presenting the Verifier Attestation JWT. This additional security measure allows the Verifier to obtain a Verifier Attestation JWT from a trusted issuer and use it for a long time independent of that issuer without the risk of an adversary impersonating the Verifier by replaying a captured attestation.[¶](#section-12-3.6)

Additional claims MAY be defined and used in the Verifier Attestation JWT, as described in \[[RFC7519](#RFC7519)\]. The Wallet MUST ignore any unrecognized claims.[¶](#section-12-4)

Verifier Attestation JWTs compliant with this specification MUST use the media type `application/verifier-attestation+jwt` as defined in [Appendix E.6.1](#va_media_type).[¶](#section-12-5)

A Verifier Attestation JWT MUST set the `typ` JOSE header to `verifier-attestation+jwt`.[¶](#section-12-6)

The Verifier Attestation JWT MAY be conveyed in the header of a JWS signed object (JOSE header).[¶](#section-12-7)

This specification introduces a JOSE header, which can be used to add a JWT to such a header as follows:[¶](#section-12-8)

*   `jwt`: This JOSE header MUST contain a JWT.[¶](#section-12-9.1)

In the context of this specification, such a JWT MUST set the `typ` JOSE header to `verifier-attestation+jwt`.[¶](#section-12-10)

