### [B.3.](#appendix-B.3) [IETF SD-JWT VC](#name-ietf-sd-jwt-vc)

This section defines how Credentials complying with \[[I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc](#I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc)\] can be presented to the Verifier using this specification.[¶](#appendix-B.3-1)

If `require_cryptographic_holder_binding` is set to `true` in the Credential Query, the Wallet MUST return an SD-JWT \[[I-D.ietf-oauth-selective-disclosure-jwt](#I-D.ietf-oauth-selective-disclosure-jwt)\] with a Key Binding JWT (SD-JWT+KB) as the Verifiable Presentation. SD-JWTs that do not support Holder Binding (i.e., do not have a `cnf` Claim) cannot be returned in this case. If `require_cryptographic_holder_binding` is set to `false`, an SD-JWT without the Key Binding JWT MAY be returned.[¶](#appendix-B.3-2)

#### [B.3.1.](#appendix-B.3.1) [Format Identifier](#name-format-identifier)

The Credential Format Identifier is `dc+sd-jwt`.[¶](#appendix-B.3.1-1)

#### [B.3.2.](#appendix-B.3.2) [Example Credential](#name-example-credential-3)

The following is a non-normative example of the unsecured payload of an IETF SD-JWT VC that will be used throughout this section:[¶](#appendix-B.3.2-1)

```
{
  "vct": "https://credentials.example.com/identity_credential",
  "given_name": "John",
  "family_name": "Doe",
  "birthdate": "1940-01-01"
}

```


[¶](#appendix-B.3.2-2)

