#### [B.3.7.](#appendix-B.3.7) [SD-JWT VCLD](#name-sd-jwt-vcld)

SD-JWT VCLD (SD-JWT Verifiable Credentials with JSON-LD) extends the IETF SD-JWT VC \[[I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc](#I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc)\] Credential format and allows to incorporate existing data models that use Linked Data, e.g., W3C VCDM \[[VC\_DATA](#VC_DATA)\], while enabling a consistent and uncomplicated approach to selective disclosure.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7-1)

Information contained in SD-JWT VCLD Credentials can be processed using a JSON-LD \[[JSON-LD](#JSON-LD)\] processor after the SD-JWT VC processing.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7-2)

When IETF SD-JWT VC is mentioned in this specification, SD-JWT VCLD defined in this section MAY be used.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7-3)

##### [B.3.7.1.](#appendix-B.3.7.1) [Format](#name-format)

SD-JWT VCLD Credentials are valid SD-JWT VCs and all requirements from \[[I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc](#I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc)\] apply. Additionally, the requirements listed in this section apply.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.1-1)

For compatibility with JWT processors, the following registered Claims from \[[RFC7519](#RFC7519)\] and \[[I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc](#I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc)\] MUST be used instead of any respective counterpart properties from W3C VCDM or elsewhere:[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.1-2)

*   `vct` to represent the type of the Credential.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.1-3.1)
*   `exp` and `nbf` to represent the validity period of SD-JWT VCLD (i.e., cryptographic signature).[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.1-3.2)
*   `iss` to represent the Credential Issuer.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.1-3.3)
*   `status` to represent the information to obtain the status of the Credential.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.1-3.4)

IETF SD-JWT VC is extended with the following claim:[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.1-4)

*   `ld`: OPTIONAL. Contains a JSON-LD \[[JSON-LD](#JSON-LD)\] object in compact form, e.g., \[[VC\_DATA](#VC_DATA)\].[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.1-5.1)

##### [B.3.7.2.](#appendix-B.3.7.2) [Processing](#name-processing-3)

The following outlines a suggested non-normative set of processing steps for SD-JWT VCLD:[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.2-1)

###### [B.3.7.2.1.](#appendix-B.3.7.2.1) [Step 1: SD-JWT VC Processing](#name-step-1-sd-jwt-vc-processing)

*   A receiver (holder or verifier) of an SD-JWT VCLD applies the processing rules outlined in Section 4 of \[[I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc](#I-D.ietf-oauth-sd-jwt-vc)\], including verifying signatures, validity periods, status information, etc.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.2.1-1.1)
*   If the `vct` value is associated with any SD-JWT VC Type Metadata, schema validation of the entire SD-JWT VCLD is performed, including the nested `ld` claim.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.2.1-1.2)
*   Additionally, trust framework rules are applied, such as ensuring the Credential Issuer is authorized to issue SD-JWT VCLDs for the specified `vct` value.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.2.1-1.3)

###### [B.3.7.2.2.](#appendix-B.3.7.2.2) [Step 2: Business Logic Processing](#name-step-2-business-logic-proce)

*   Once the SD-JWT VC is verified and trusted by the SD-JWT VC processor, and if the `ld` claim is present, the receiver extracts the JSON-LD object from the `ld` claim and uses this for the business logic object. If the `ld` claim is not present, the entire SD-JWT VC is considered to represent the business logic object.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.2.2-1.1)
*   The business logic object is then passed on for further use case-specific processing and validation. The business logic assumes that all security-critical functions (e.g., signature verification, trusted issuer) have already been performed during the previous step. Additional schema validation is applied if provided in the `ld` claim, e.g., to support SHACL schemas. Note that while a `vct` claim is required, SD-JWT VC type metadata resolution and related schema validation is optional in certain cases.[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.2.2-1.2)

##### [B.3.7.3.](#appendix-B.3.7.3) [Examples](#name-examples-3)

The following is a non-normative example of an unsecured payload of an SD-JWT VCLD (i.e., before applying the modifications to enable selective disclosure and before adding validity claims).[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.3-1)

```
{
  "vct": "https://credentials.example.com/example_credential",
  "ld": {
    "@context": [
      "https://www.w3.org/ns/credentials/v2",
      "https://w3id.org/citizenship/v3"
    ],
    "credentialSubject": {
      "givenName": "John",
      "familyName": "Doe",
      "birthDate": "1978-07-17"
    }
  }
}

```


[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.3-2)

The following payload would be used in the SD-JWT after encoding the payload above and enabling selective disclosure on the End-User specific claims within `credentialSubject`:[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.3-3)

```
{
  "iss": "https://issuer.example.com",
  "iat": 1683000000,
  "exp": 1883000000,
  "vct": "https://credentials.example.com/example_credential",
  "ld": {
    "@context": [
      "https://www.w3.org/ns/credentials/v2",
      "https://w3id.org/citizenship/v3"
    ],
    "credentialSubject": {
      "_sd": [
        "6BJdQrO24ejTTMsFI-wGiJJmGrbseWc5IwCCp4NAJ0k",
        "NTDVsbVAwS9AnUVq-_YG_wv0yGD0bv2JstX-AmvN65I",
        "ts0pyPntLjD0_NcgNOI3hd_2WjbZw21p2LfqhOC0b-U"
      ]
    }
  },
  "_sd_alg": "sha-256",
  "cnf": {
    "jwk": {
      "kty": "EC",
      "crv": "P-256",
      "x": "TCAER19Zvu3OHF4j4W4vfSVoHIP1ILilDls7vCeGemc",
      "y": "ZxjiWWbZMQGHVWKVQ4hbSIirsVfuecCE6t4jT9F2HZQ"
    }
  }
}

```


[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.3-4)

Note: The decision which claims to make selectively disclosable is up to the Issuer of the Credential. Considerations can be found in Section 6 and Section 9.7 of \[[I-D.ietf-oauth-selective-disclosure-jwt](#I-D.ietf-oauth-selective-disclosure-jwt)\].[¶](#appendix-B.3.7.3-5)

[Appendix C.](#appendix-C) [Combining this specification with SIOPv2](#name-combining-this-specificatio)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This section shows how SIOP and OpenID for Verifiable Presentations can be combined to present Credentials and pseudonymously authenticate an End-User using subject controlled key material.[¶](#appendix-C-1)

### [C.1.](#appendix-C.1) [Request](#name-request-2)

The following is a non-normative example of a request that combines this specification and \[[SIOPv2](#SIOPv2)\].[¶](#appendix-C.1-1)

```
GET /authorize?
  response_type=vp_token%20id_token
  &scope=openid
  &id_token_type=subject_signed
  &client_id=x509_san_dns%3Aclient.example.org
  &redirect_uri=https%3A%2F%2Fclient.example.org%2Fcb
  &dcql_query=...
  &nonce=n-0S6_WzA2Mj HTTP/1.1
Host: wallet.example.com

```


[¶](#appendix-C.1-2)

The differences to the example requests in the previous sections are:[¶](#appendix-C.1-3)

*   `response_type` is set to `vp_token id_token`. This means the Wallet returns the `vp_token` parameter in the same response as the `id_token` parameter as described in [Section 8](#response).[¶](#appendix-C.1-4.1)
*   The request includes the `scope` parameter with value `openid` making this an OpenID Connect request. Additionally, the request also contains the parameter `id_token_type` with value `subject_signed` requesting a Self-Issuer ID Token, i.e., the request is a SIOP request.[¶](#appendix-C.1-4.2)

### [C.2.](#appendix-C.2) [Response](#name-response-3)

The following is a non-normative example of a response sent upon receiving a request provided in [Appendix C.1](#siop_request):[¶](#appendix-C.2-1)

```
HTTP/1.1 302 Found
Location: https://client.example.org/cb#
  id_token=
  &vp_token=...

```


[¶](#appendix-C.2-2)

In addition to the `vp_token`, it also contains an `id_token`.[¶](#appendix-C.2-3)

The following is a non-normative example of the payload of a Self-Issued ID Token \[[SIOPv2](#SIOPv2)\] contained in the above response:[¶](#appendix-C.2-4)

```
{
  "iss": "did:example:NzbLsXh8uDCcd6MNwXF4W7noWXFZAfHkxZsRGC9Xs",
  "sub": "did:example:NzbLsXh8uDCcd6MNwXF4W7noWXFZAfHkxZsRGC9Xs",
  "aud": "x509_san_dns:client.example.org",
  "nonce": "n-0S6_WzA2Mj",
  "exp": 1311281970,
  "iat": 1311280970
}

```


[¶](#appendix-C.2-5)

Note: The `nonce` and `aud` are set to the `nonce` of the request and the Client Identifier of the Verifier, respectively, in the same way as for the Verifier, Verifiable Presentations to prevent replay.[¶](#appendix-C.2-6)

